- "Established before the dawn of the new millennium" refers to funds established before January 1, 2000;
- "Outperformed the average 5-year pre-tax return" means the fund's average return rate is higher than the average return rate of all funds over a 5-year period before taxes;
- "Reviewed by financial analysts in the last year" refers to the number of times financial analysts have accessed the fund for viewing after January 1, 2022.

- "Top-performing funds" refers to funds with the highest return rates within their respective categories;
- "User access patterns" include metrics such as the number of unique users, total accesses, and total duration of access for each fund;
- "5-year return before taxes" is a specific return type and time period used in the financial industry to evaluate fund performance.

- 'new year began' refers to January 1, 2022;
- 'explored more than one fund in their journey' means the analysts have accessed more than one distinct fund;
- 'equity funds' are mutual funds that primarily invest in stocks.

- "Top 5 performing funds" refers to the funds with the highest return rates within each time period;
- "Cumulative return rate" is the sum of return rates for the top 5 funds in each time period;
- "Time periods" include 1 year, 5 years, 10 years, and since inception.

- 'Top-performing' refers to funds ranked in the top 3 within their performance category based on return rate;
- 'Frequently accessed' refers to users who have accessed funds more than once;
- 'Performance category' is categorized as 'Short-term' (1 year), 'Medium-term' (5 years), and 'Long-term' (all other periods).

- "birth dates" refers to the inception dates of the mutual funds;
- "seen more than one visitor" implies that the fund has had more than one access event;
- "times accessed" refers to the count of access events;
- "total duration of these visits" refers to the sum of the durations of all access events.

- 'Fixed Income' refers to investment assets that provide a return in the form of fixed periodic payments and eventual return of principal at maturity;
- 'Higher maintenance costs' refers to annual management fees greater than 0.5%;
- 'Visited more than once' means the fund has been accessed more than once in the access logs.

- 'Growth equity funds' are mutual funds that focus on investing in companies with high growth potential;
- 'Return rates' are expressed as percentages and represent the performance of the funds over specific time periods;
- 'Time periods' can include 5 years, 10 years, or since inception, but not 1 year.

- The Sharpe ratio is a measure of risk-adjusted return, where a higher value indicates better performance relative to the risk taken;
- Asset classes include categories such as equity, fixed income, and others, each representing different types of investments;
- The time period '1 year' refers to the most recent one-year period for which return data is available.

- 'High management fee' refers to a management fee greater than 0.8%;
- 'Low minimum investment' refers to a minimum investment less than $1000;
- 'Good performance' refers to an average return rate greater than 5% over the last year.

- "born before the dawn of the new millennium" refers to funds established before January 1, 2000;
- "management fee that's lighter than a feather" refers to an annual management fee of less than 1%;
- "average return rate that outshines the sun" refers to an average return rate higher than the overall average return rate across all returns.

- "Consistently outperformed" refers to the fund being ranked first in return rate for each time period;
- "Most visited by users" refers to the fund with the highest access count based on user access logs;
- "Shining beacon in a sea of investment options" is a metaphor for a highly sought-after and top-performing mutual fund.

- A "top-performing fund" refers to a fund that is ranked 1st in return rate over the past year;
- "Active users" are users who have accessed the system at least once;
- The average 1-year return rate is calculated by averaging the 1-year return rates of all funds managed by each fund manager.

- A high Sharpe ratio indicates a good risk-adjusted return; a low beta value indicates lower sensitivity to market movements;
- 'Phoenix' is a metaphor for funds that exhibit exceptional performance and stability;
- 'Explorers' refers to users who have accessed the funds;
- 'Navigating' refers to the duration of user access.
